Analyzing the crimes committed in San Fransisco from June 2003 to May 2015

Rohan Thakkar

October 24, 2015

As my attempt to predict the category of crimes that occurred in the city by the bay, the dataset retrieved from https://www.kaggle.com/c/sf-crime is a collection of all crimes committed in San Fransisco during the period of 6 June, 2003 to 13 May, 2015.

Since the number of rows is pretty huge (878049!!!), I will display the names of columns of the dataset -

##       [,1]        
##  [1,] "Dates"     
##  [2,] "Category"  
##  [3,] "Descript"  
##  [4,] "DayOfWeek" 
##  [5,] "PdDistrict"
##  [6,] "Resolution"
##  [7,] "Address"   
##  [8,] "X"         
##  [9,] "Y"

Other than the five self-explanatory columns,

  • PdDistrict represents the district of the police department that was responsible of curbing the crime.

  • Resolution represents the outcome of investigation on crime.

  • X represents the X co-ordinate of the location where the crime took place.

  • Y represents the Y co-ordinate of the location where the crime took place.

Analysis 1 - Calculating the number of crimes for each district to determine the one with maximum occurences of crime.

As we can see from the above graph, the Bayview district has recorded the highest number of crimes and can, thus, be predicted to be at the highest danger.

Analysis 2 - Calculating the number of crimes for each district to determine the one with maximum occurences of crime.

Friday has, thus, observed higher crimes than any other day in the history and is, thus, considered as the least safe day to hang around at San Fransisco.

Analysis 3 - To find out the outcome of the investigation of the convicted for each crime

Unfortunately, more criminals have been unfounded than the number of criminals in any other type of crime.

The next largest observed outcome is Arrest - cited which restores hope of the SF residents out there.

Analysis 4 - Calculating the number of each type of crime committed

The most common type of crime committed is Secondary Codes.
